 and Development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">covers the following topics which directly pertain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to this inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Approach to Disability</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The strength of the evidence base</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Integration of disability issues within sector programs </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The financial costs and benefits of an increased emphasis on disability</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Partnership</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s and c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onsultation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Post-2015 development</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Issues and Approach to Disability</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One billion people, or 15 percent of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> world’s population, experience some form of disability. One-fifth of the estimated global total, or between 110 million and 190 million people, encounter significant disabilities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Persons with disabilities, on average as a group, are more likely to exper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ience adverse socioeconomic outcomes than persons without disabilities, such as less education, worse health outcomes, less employment, and higher poverty rates. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The development consequences of disability should not be ignored. And unless persons with dis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ability are included into the post-2015 development agenda, this agenda will fail to be truly inclusive.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Understanding of exclusion and marginalization </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> key, as is ensuring that disabled people can both contribute to this goal and benefit from the fruits of growth. In the work that we do with developing countries, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we have embraced the ideals of mainstreaming of disability, so that persons with disabilitie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> benefit from our development interventions on an equal basis as others. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The strength of the evidence base</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The first-ever </span><a href="http://www.worldbank.org/disability/worldreport"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">World Report on Disability</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (co-authored by the World Bank and the World Health Organization) documents the current state of disability, using the best evidence available.  The report:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">presents a number of recommendations to improve the circumstances of persons with by the key actor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">documents that a major impediment to understanding of disability and to the development and implementation of disability inclusion policies is the lack of accurate and comparable data on disability both at national and international levels.</span></li></ul></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.1pt; padding-left:3.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The World Ba</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nk Group, in collaboration with the World Health Organization, is developing the Model Disability Survey (MDS), which will address the lack of data, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and begin to provide the data necessary to quantify the impact of increased participation by persons with d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isabilities in social and economic activities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have commission research to analyze available disability data, such as </span><a href="http://imagebank.worldbank.org/servlet/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2011/06/16/000386194_20110616042613/Rendered/PDF/625640NWP0110900PUBLIC00BOX361487B.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Disability and poverty in developing countries: a snapshot from the world health survey</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-w